Schemas — struct-type versus the D-D-L string.

There are two ways to define a schema, and both produce the exact same result, so pick whichever reads better in your code.

The first is programmatic. You build a struct-type out of struct-fields — one field per column, each with a name and a type. It is verbose and explicit, and it is easy to build up from code.

The second is a D-D-L string. You write the columns as one sequel-flavored string — for example, transaction-id string, amount decimal, timestamp. It is compact and easy to paste.

Now, here is the rule that matters. Always prefer an explicit schema in production. Schema inference does work, but it triggers a full scan of the data, just to decide the types. That is slow on large datasets. And it can guess wrong — for instance, reading a sparse is-flagged column as a string, when what you actually wanted was a boolean.
